1 SECTION 8. ORS 468B.513 is amended to read:
2 468B.513. (1) The owner or operator of a bulk oils or liquid fuels terminal shall properly imple-
3 ment a seismic risk mitigation implementation plan that has been approved by the Department of
4 Environmental Quality. A seismic risk mitigation implementation plan must, at a minimum, identify
5 actions, with timelines, to protect public health, life safety and environmental safety within the fa-
6 cility, in areas adjacent to the facility and in other areas that may be affected as a result of damages
7 to the facility. A seismic risk mitigation implementation plan, as a risk-based assessment, must in-
8 clude consideration of the likelihood of a magnitude 9.0 Cascadia Subduction Zone earthquake, the
9 potential consequences of that event and the resources needed to respond to that event.
10 (2) The Environmental Quality Commission, in consultation with the State Department of
11 Geology and Mineral Industries, shall adopt by rule a seismic risk mitigation implementation pro-
12 gram for bulk oils or liquid fuels terminals that is based on risk. To the extent feasible and appro-
13 priate, the program adopted under this section shall be consistent and coordinated with the program
14 established under ORS 468B.345 to 468B.415. Rules adopted under this section shall include, but not
15 be limited to:
16 (a) Rules for the required content of seismic risk mitigation implementation plans and rules for
17 approval by the Department of Environmental Quality of seismic risk mitigation implementation
18 plans.
19 (b) Provisions for training, response exercises, external peer reviews, inspections and tests in
20 order to verify the ability of the facility to sustain safe conditions and respond to uncontrolled re-
21 leases of hazardous materials from the bulk oils or liquid fuels terminal due to an earthquake.
22 (c) Requirements to minimize harmful impacts to local communities and natural resources due
23 to uncontrolled releases of hazardous materials from the bulk oils or liquid fuels terminal due to an
24 earthquake and its associated direct and indirect impacts, including fires and flooding.
25 (d) Requirements for the inspection of bulk storage tanks at bulk oils or liquid fuels terminals.
26 (e) Design and construction standards for new bulk storage tanks constructed at bulk oils or
27 liquid fuels terminals.
28 (f) Design and construction standards for seismic mitigation of existing bulk storage tanks, pip-
29 ing and related structures constructed at bulk oils or liquid fuels terminals.
30 (g) Provisions requiring the proper installation of seismically certified generators to power
31 critical operations, or at a minimum, the installation of electrical hookups for emergency generators.
32 (h) Provisions for the review of seismic vulnerability assessments required under ORS 468B.510
33 and seismic risk mitigation implementation plans required under subsection (1) of this section by
34 state agencies with expertise in earthquake hazards, risk mitigation or emergency preparedness or
35 management.
36 (i) Provisions requiring the owner or operator of a bulk oils or liquid fuels terminal to submit
37 seismic vulnerability mitigation implementation plan updates to the department:
38 (A) According to a schedule established by the commission;
39 (B) Upon the retrofit or reconstruction of all or a part of a bulk oils or liquid fuels terminal;
40 and
41 (C) Based on new scientific or technical findings, but no more frequently than once every three
42 years.
43 (j) Provisions establishing a fee calculated to cover the costs to the department of [reviewing
44 seismic risk mitigation implementation plans submitted under this section and seismic risk assessments
45 submitted under ORS 468B.510,] carrying out ORS 468B.510 to 468B.525, less any federal funds
